I won't flame you Shokran.  I know many enchanters that are <I>really</I> good, who never use charm in a serious fight situation.  I'm not one of those people, but there's nothing wrong with not using charm.<P>Just learn how to use it, as it's an enchanter skill that requires some practice, I assure you.  Now, some good points have been made...<P>Tashania everything to aid in a longer lasting charm, plus aid in rooting.<P>Beguile if possible (stonegazers & gnashers should not break 39) so that you can use Color Shift to cover the recharm.<P>Root the enemy mob at all times to make most recharms much safer.<P>Attack Slow mobs instead of hasting pet for increased safety, and your pet will actually get more kills in most times.  Unless you have a misconning pet (like some velious mobs or griffawns etc) that hits much harder than it should, don't use haste as it won't make the pet last longer than an attack slow will.  Haste allows you to rely on charm less (by about 30 seconds in comparison) as the fight is faster, but the pet will usually need help for the 2nd fight if its a "normal" mob.<P>Don't dick with spiders, their poison is basically a DOT to screw mezzing plans over.<P>If you use Cajoling Whispers, then load up level 4 Mesmerize to cover the casting time of the charm, which even Color Skew only covers if you backpedal a <I>lot</I>.<P>Charm is a risk for reward, extreme to both sides.<P>And yes, you will have nights where you just suck.  It happens.  Don't lose faith if you want to learn charming--but don't charm out of peer pressure, either--as I won't think less of you, p(_)ssy.   <IMG SRC="tongue.gif" border="0"><P>Oh, and get a healer partner for the start, makes things a lot easier.<P>--------------------<P>Eugee<P><A HREF="http://www.cyberjunkie.com/eugee" TARGET=_blank>Xornn's Guide to Enchanting</A><P><I>"You know, we scientists learned long ago that human interaction was impossible to predict; so we left that up to the philosophers... and poets."</I>
</FONT>
